# Accessibility


## Rules

1. All interactive elements must be keyboard-accessible
2. All images must have descriptive `alt` text (or `alt=""` for decorative images)
3. Use semantic HTML elements (`<nav>`, `<main>`, `<article>`, `<button>`, etc.)
4. Form inputs must have associated `<label>` elements
5. Color must not be the sole means of conveying information
6. Maintain sufficient color contrast ratios (4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for large text)
7. ARIA attributes should supplement, not replace, semantic HTML

## Testing Tools

- testing-library

Run accessibility tests before submitting UI changes.

## ARIA Patterns

This project uses ARIA attributes. Follow these guidelines:
- Use `aria-label` for elements without visible text
- Use `aria-describedby` for additional descriptions
- Use `aria-live` regions for dynamic content updates
- Use `role` attributes only when semantic HTML is insufficient

## Company Accessibility Standards

- **A11Y-001** (high): All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible.
- **A11Y-002** (high): All images must have alt text. Decorative images use alt="".
- **A11Y-003** (high): Use semantic HTML elements (button, nav, main, article) instead of generic divs with click handlers.
- **A11Y-004** (medium): Color must not be the only means of conveying information.
- **A11Y-005** (medium): Ensure sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA minimum — 4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for large text).

## Semantic HTML

Score: **low**

> Use semantic HTML elements (nav, main, article, section) instead of generic divs.






## Checklist

Before submitting any UI change:

- [ ] Keyboard navigation works (Tab, Enter, Escape, Arrow keys)
- [ ] Screen reader announces content correctly
- [ ] Focus indicators are visible
- [ ] Color contrast meets minimum ratios
- [ ] No content is lost when zoomed to 200%
